      <h2>Why Apple Cider Vinegar Gummies Became a $1 Billion Category</h2>

      <p>Apple cider vinegar has been used as a folk remedy for centuries, but the modern ACV gummy market did not exist before 2019. That year, a Los Angeles-based company called Goli launched what would become the fastest-selling supplement in Amazon history, generating over <strong>$10 million in revenue within its first six months</strong>. By 2025, the global ACV gummy market had surpassed $1 billion in annual sales, with dozens of brands competing for shelf space at Walmart, Target, and Whole Foods.</p>

      <p>The appeal is straightforward. Liquid apple cider vinegar is notoriously unpleasant to drink. It burns the throat, damages tooth enamel on direct contact, and has a taste that most people find genuinely difficult to tolerate. Gummies eliminated every one of those barriers while packaging the core active ingredient — <strong>acetic acid</strong> — into a format that tastes like a piece of candy. For millions of consumers, ACV gummies made a centuries-old remedy accessible for the first time.</p>

      <p>But here is the critical question that most review sites avoid: <strong>do ACV gummies deliver enough acetic acid to actually produce measurable health effects?</strong> The published research on apple cider vinegar overwhelmingly uses liquid ACV at doses of 1 to 2 tablespoons per day (approximately 750 to 1,500 milligrams of acetic acid). Most gummies deliver 500 milligrams of ACV per serving — not 500 milligrams of pure acetic acid. Since ACV is roughly 5% acetic acid by volume, a 500mg ACV gummy contains approximately 25 milligrams of acetic acid. That is a fraction of what clinical studies have used.</p>

      <p>This does not mean ACV gummies are worthless. It means that realistic expectations are essential. Throughout this guide, we will distinguish between what the science has demonstrated using liquid ACV at clinical doses, what can reasonably be expected from gummy formulations, and where marketing claims outpace the evidence. We purchased and tested over 40 ACV gummies from major retailers and direct-to-consumer brands. Every product was evaluated on acetic acid content, additional ingredients, taste, digestive tolerability, and value per serving.</p>
