    <section>
      <h2>ACV Gummy Ingredients: What the Science Actually Shows</h2>

      <div class="ing-box">
        <h3>Acetic Acid: The Active Compound</h3>
        <p>Every claimed benefit of apple cider vinegar traces back to a single molecule: <strong>acetic acid</strong>. ACV is approximately 5-6% acetic acid by volume, with the remainder being water and trace compounds. When you see "500mg of apple cider vinegar" on a gummy label, you are getting roughly 25-30mg of actual acetic acid — the compound responsible for the health effects studied in published research.</p>

        <p>This distinction between ACV volume and acetic acid content is critical for setting realistic expectations. The most frequently cited studies on ACV used liquid vinegar at doses of 15-30mL (1-2 tablespoons) per day, which delivers approximately 750-1,500mg of acetic acid. Even the highest-dose gummies on our list (1,000mg ACV) provide only about 50-60mg of acetic acid per serving. This is a significant dosage gap between what researchers studied and what gummies deliver.</p>

