    <!-- FAQ -->
    <section>
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions About Apple Cider Vinegar Gummies</h2>

      <details class="fq">
        <summary>Do apple cider vinegar gummies actually work?</summary>
        <p>ACV gummies contain acetic acid, the active compound in liquid apple cider vinegar. Small clinical studies suggest acetic acid may support blood sugar regulation and appetite management when consumed at sufficient doses. However, most gummies deliver 500mg of ACV per serving, which provides approximately 25-30mg of acetic acid — significantly less than the 750-1,500mg used in published research (1-2 tablespoons of liquid ACV). Benefits are modest and work best alongside a balanced diet and regular exercise. They are not a substitute for medical treatment or proven weight loss strategies.</p>
      </details>

      <details class="fq">
        <summary>Are ACV gummies as effective as liquid apple cider vinegar?</summary>
        <p>Liquid ACV typically delivers more acetic acid per serving than gummies. One tablespoon of liquid ACV contains roughly 750mg of acetic acid, while most gummies provide 500mg of ACV (not pure acetic acid — actual acetic acid content is approximately 25-30mg). However, gummies eliminate the harsh taste and potential tooth enamel damage associated with drinking undiluted vinegar. For people who cannot tolerate liquid ACV, gummies offer a more palatable alternative with reduced potency. If maximum acetic acid intake is your goal, liquid ACV is more efficient.</p>
      </details>

      <details class="fq">
        <summary>Can ACV gummies damage your teeth?</summary>
        <p>ACV gummies are less damaging to tooth enamel than liquid apple cider vinegar because the acetic acid is encapsulated within the gummy matrix rather than directly coating your teeth. However, gummies do contain sugar and citric acid, which can contribute to enamel erosion if consumed excessively. To minimize risk, rinse your mouth with water after taking ACV gummies and avoid brushing your teeth for at least 30 minutes afterward — brushing while enamel is softened from acid exposure can cause additional damage. Limit your intake to the recommended serving size.</p>
      </details>

      <details class="fq">
        <summary>What are the side effects of ACV gummies?</summary>
        <p>The most commonly reported side effects include nausea, digestive discomfort, and bloating, particularly when taken on an empty stomach. Some users experience acid reflux or heartburn due to the acetic acid content. ACV may also interact with certain medications, including diuretics, insulin, and digoxin, by affecting potassium levels or blood sugar regulation. Start with one gummy per day to assess your tolerance before increasing to the full recommended serving. Discontinue use and consult a healthcare provider if you experience persistent discomfort.</p>
      </details>

      <details class="fq">
        <summary>Do ACV gummies help with blood sugar?</summary>
        <p>Several small studies suggest that acetic acid may improve insulin sensitivity and reduce post-meal blood sugar spikes when consumed before or with carbohydrate-rich meals. A 2004 study published in Diabetes Care found that vinegar improved insulin sensitivity by 19-34% during a high-carb meal in insulin-resistant subjects. However, these studies used liquid vinegar at concentrations significantly higher than what gummies provide. ACV gummies should not replace prescribed blood sugar medications, and individuals with diabetes should consult their physician before adding any ACV supplement to their regimen.</p>
      </details>

      <details class="fq">
        <summary>Should I take ACV gummies with meals or on an empty stomach?</summary>
        <p>Most manufacturers recommend taking ACV gummies before meals. If your goal is blood sugar management, taking them 15-20 minutes before a carbohydrate-rich meal may help moderate the glycemic response based on the available research on liquid ACV. If you experience nausea or stomach discomfort on an empty stomach, take them with food instead — the digestive benefits are not significantly diminished. Avoid taking ACV gummies immediately before bed, as the acetic acid content may cause acid reflux when lying down.</p>
      </details>

      <details class="fq">
        <summary>What does "the Mother" mean in ACV gummies?</summary>
        <p>"The Mother" refers to the colony of beneficial bacteria (primarily acetobacter species) that forms during the natural fermentation process of apple cider vinegar. It appears as cloudy strands in unfiltered ACV and contains probiotics, enzymes, and proteins. Brands like Goli, Bragg, and Garden of Life include "the Mother" in their gummies, which may offer additional gut health benefits beyond acetic acid alone. However, the probiotic content in gummies is typically lower than in raw, unfiltered liquid ACV, and the bacterial strains differ from those in dedicated probiotic supplements.</p>
      </details>

      <details class="fq">
        <summary>How long does it take for ACV gummies to work?</summary>
        <p>Effects vary depending on your health goal and individual physiology. For digestive comfort and reduced bloating, some users report noticeable improvements within 1-2 weeks of consistent daily use. For measurable changes in blood sugar response or appetite management, most clinical studies observed effects after 4-12 weeks of daily supplementation. Any weight management benefits are gradual and require ongoing use alongside dietary and lifestyle changes. ACV gummies are not a rapid-results supplement — consistency over weeks and months is what produces outcomes.</p>
      </details>
    </section>

